Pitt’s trustees endorsed a proposal
Thursday to allow students to ride
Port Authority Transit buses any-
where in Allegheny County free of
charge.

The board’s Student Affairs
Committee Voted to increase stu-
dents’ security, safety and transporta-
tion fee to-$55 per semester for both
full- and part-time students.

Since 1997 the fee has been $37
per semester for
full-time and $16
per semester for
part-time students.

The increase
would take effect
at the beginning of
the fall 1998-99
semester.

If the full
board of trustees
votes in favor of
the plan at its June
25 meeting, stu-
dents would be
able to use their ID '
cards to ride Port
Authority buses
and light rail vehi-
cles anywhere in
Allegheny County.

Pitt would use
the increased secu-
rity, safety and
transportation fee
to pay PAT for the
service.

The plan. would not affect current
University shuttle service. However,
Pitt spokesman Ken Service cau-
tioned the proposal would be a
“demonstration project” for the first
year.

Service said the University could
adjust the plan for cost if the number
of riders turns out to be higher or
lower than current estimates. Other
factors might also arise, he said, as
the plan is utilized and Pitt identifies
unforeseen complications.

If cost or other factors indicate
the proposal is not feasible for the
long term, administration could abol-
ish it, Service said.

But he added “most people feel
pretty confident” the plan would work
out.

In April, students exercised a rare
opportunity to affect administrative
policy-making when the Department
of Parking and Transportation asked

