I’m not exactly a June Cleaver

. wannabe. I couldn’t care less about how

Snuggle-soft my towels are, and as for the
carpet — well, I, like nature, abhor a vacu-
um.

I have exactly one arguably domestic
talent I can cook

The art: of preparing food is one of the
most misunderstood, ranking somewhere on
the scale between abstract expressionism
and interpretive dance involving blue—paint—
ed nudes and Silly String. People think of
cooking as a pastime for the mild-rnannered,
the mother hen, yes, the woman.

This is, need you ask, bull. First off, do
you know how many of the world’s master
chefs are women? Neither do I, but it’s a
small number, I know that Professional

I kitchens are famously stressful workplaces,

and are slightly less likely to become truly
non—sexist environments than the Aberdeen

 ‘ Proving Ground

But what about devoted amateurs like
me, the people who spend hours of their free
time trying to perfect their lemon souﬂle, the
people who consult “The New York Times
Cookbook” far more frequently than any of
the inspired texts of the world’s major reli-

gions? What drives us?

Cooking feeds animal urges beyond the

most obvious — hunger. It provides an out-
let for basic human emotions. It allows you
to be completely civilized on the outside
while providing a pressure valve for socially
unacceptable impulses. e ,

One of the great things many peo- ,_
ple don’t realize about cook- //
ing is how aggressive it real- »,
ly is. Chopping. Pounding. 
Kneading. Whipping. Better 
to sink a knife into a
mushroom, I I
say, than
i n t o a
your
neigh-
b o r . 
(Unless, of
course, your
upstairs neighbor
is getting jiggy
with it at 3 am, in
which case no jury in
the world will \hold you
responsible.)

For the homicidal maniac in you, try
cooking lobster. You plunge them into boil-
ing water and try to convince yourself
they’re just clattering around in that pan

2

  
   
 
 
 
  
  
 
 
  

 

because of an automatic neuromuscular
reaction. Then you drown your sorrows in
drawn butter.

Cooking is also great for control freaks.
Except for stuff like Christmas cookies,
foods are generally most easily prepared by
one person. This means no sharing of
authority, no passing the buck, for the fate of
the world.

I’m calming down now. Really.

Cooking takes a certain amount of guts
and endurance, though. You have to be
ready to think and act quickly. It’s a
t metaphor for life. Hey, my man Hany

- Truman said it —— “If you can’t
stand the heat, get out of the
kitchen.”
The thing about cooks
you have to realize is we’re
obsessive because we have a
se1f—feeding addiction. We
make good food, we start to
expect good food, we get to the
V point where nothing is acceptable
but the best.

You exhibit certain symptoms when
you start to become a foodie. (I hate that
word, but at least it sounds less pretentious
than “gourme ’ or “epicure.”) You start to do
things like packing a lunch not because
you’re broke but because you can’t ﬁnd a

decent green salad in Oakland You can no
longer eat margarine because it has an effect
on your palate like licking the ﬂoor in a
petroleum—based fertilizer factory. You start
referring to your favorite cookbook authors
by ﬁrst name: Craig, Julia, Irma. (Claiborne,
Child and Rombauer. You hate the new edi-
tion of “The Joy of Cooking.” By the way,
like New Coke, it just ain’t the real thing.)

Cooking is a big component of inde-
pendence. If you can’t do really simple
things — cooking frozen vegetables, for
instance, or frying an egg — you will always
be beholden either to someone else to cook
for you or to prepackaged food. Do you real-
ly want to spend your entire life existing on
Ramen noodles and Stouffer’s French bread
pizza?

Moreover, being able to make your own
food lets you manifest your individuality.
You don’t like nuts in sweet rolls? Don’t use
them. Want pizza with sliced grapefruit and
guacamole? Then you’re a strange little
duck, but go for it anyway.

Food is like a lot ofthings in life — it’s
not so much what you’re given, but instead
what you do with it. And it deserves to be
savored instead of just gotten over with.

