Recently in San Francisco, U.S.
District court judge Charles Breyer ordered
six medical marijuana clubs to be closed for
violation of the Controlled Substance Act.
The clubs provide marijuana to individuals
suffering from theside effects of AIDS and
cancer treatments, as well as to persons
afflicted by disorders such as multiple scle-
rosis and muscular dystrophy. The club
owners pledge to keep the clubs open until
they have their day in court.

These are the men and women whose
sutferings are both neglected and prolonged
by an often questioned, half- century—old
political agenda, laid out by none other than
the United States most corrupt public oﬂi—
cial to date, J. Edgar Hoover. This is the man
who denied the existence of any organized
crime in his decades as director of the FBI.

(Also, the proﬁts from the sale of mari-
juana and other illegal substances do not
end up in the pockets of small time dealers
and growers, but in the pockets of the drug
cartel barons. These individuals are not the
inmates in our federal and state prisons.
They are far enough away from local dis-
tributors to avoid prosecution.

As our prisons ﬁll with non—violent
marijuana oﬂenders to levels that exceed
the per capita rate of any other democratic
nation, one must begin to ask if our federal
govermnent’s methods in curbing drug use

marijuana laws infringe on rights

are excessive or even eﬂ’ective. There are
twice as many teenage marijuana users
today as there were in 1990, just about ﬁf-
teen years after the “Just Say No” campaign
began. Aren’t our children the ones we
believed we’d be saving by subscribing to
this anti-drug propaganda and “war on
drugs”?

War uniﬁes support for a weak admin-
istration, it diverts money from the citizens’
pockets, and it gives constitutional cause to
infringe on citizens’ privacy and personal
liberties. The red threat, now gone, has left
the American war machine without a target.
The funds are now allocated to break down
the barrier set by our forefathers to prevent
our country falling into a fascist state: the
Bill of Rights. Our liberties are trashed with
each penny spent to spy on, manipulate and
incarcerate citizens who choose to ignite a
joint after a hard day’s work or, God forbid,
try to lessen slightly the painful effects of
chemotherapy. '

The World Health Organization recent-
ly released a report on the global effects of
marijuana. It found that the use of marijua-
na worldwide had insigniﬁcant negative
effects on health and social welfare, espe-
cially when compared with the use of nico-
tine and alcohol. The report went on to say
that even if marijuana use were to increase
to the levels of these other two drugs, their
ﬁnding would most likely be the same. The
report’s release was delayed for several
months due to pressure from, who else, the

United States government. The U.S. gov-
ernment has also been instrumental in
delaying medical marijuana legalization in
Canada, Great Britain, France and
Germany. All fear the political and econom-
ic sanctions promised by U.S. policy-mak-
ers for narcotics decriminalization. Our
diplomats have even strongly discouraged
foreign doctors and scientists from
researching the possible beneﬁts of marijua-
na.

Most marijuana addicts reported by the
government are usually people who have
chosen to go into treatment to avoid or
lessen their prison sentences, although mar-
ijuana addiction is somewhat of a myth any-
way. There is no chemical addiction like
that of nicotine, heroin and even alcohol. An
addict of any one of these substances shows
serious withdrawal symptoms, while mari-
juana users seem to be able to walk away
from the drug without serious conse-
quences. The greatest danger to marijuana
users comes not from the drug itself, but
from the law— enforcement officials wh
hunt them down like dogs. -

Anyone who has experimented with
marijuana will generally say that although
there may be better ways to spend your time
and money, it is quite harmless. Abuse and
overuse of any substance can be detrimental
to your health. Eat too much and you get fat.
Drink too much alcohol and problems
ensue, though even the use of alcohol in
moderation has been found to lessen your

chances of heart disease. Let’s get drug
addicts out of prison and into treatment, and
let responsible adults make ﬂieir own deci-
sions about the use of recreational drugs.
There are more drugs in any one prison than
Hunter S. Thompson and Trmotlry Leary
have seen in ﬂieir whole lives. It costs more
toputadrugdealerinprisonthantoputhim
into treatment, and treatment is twice as
